Since we have an isosceles trapezoid, the base angles are equal. We're given that one of the smaller base angles is $60^\circ$.  The altitude of the trapezoid forms a 30-60-90 right triangle with half of the longer base and one of the legs of the trapezoid.

Recall the side ratios in a 30-60-90 triangle: $1:\sqrt{3}:2$.  We know the altitude (opposite the $60^\circ$ angle) is $2\sqrt{3}$ inches. This means the shorter leg of the triangle (which is half the length of the longer base) is $2\sqrt{3}/\sqrt{3} = 2$ inches.

Therefore, the longer base is twice the length of the shorter leg, making it $2 \cdot 2 = 4$ inches.

Finally, the perimeter of the trapezoid is the sum of all its sides: $5 + 4 + 5 + 4 = 18$ inches. 

\begin{align*}
\boxed{18}
\end{align*}

